                           an examination of the army that General William Tecumseh Sherman commanded through <u7:country-region u2:st="on"><st1:country-region
                           w:st="on">Georgia</st1:country-region> and the <u8:place u2:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Carolinas</st1:place>, in late 1864
                           and early 1865. Instead of being just another narrative of the March to the Sea and Carolina Campaigns, however, Glatthaar's
                           book is a look at the individuals that composed the army. He examines the social and ideological backgrounds of the men in
                           <u9:City u2:st="on"><u9:place u2:st="on"><st1:City w:st="on"><st1:place w:st="on">Sherman</st1:place></st1:City>'s army, and
                           evaluates how they felt about various factors of the war--slavery, the union, and, most significantly, the campaign in which
                           they were participating. Continued below&#8230;</SPAN><SPAN style="COLOR: black"><?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = "urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office"
